the prices charged for the same goods in their home market. In order to state a claim, a plaintiff must show both that
such lower prices were commonly and systematically charged, and that the importer had the specific intent to injure
or destroy an industry in the United States, or to prevent the establishment of an industry. Dumping cases are more
commonly brought using the administrative procedures of the Tariff Act of 1930, discussed below.


